    <svcsection/>
    <svcsection id="s05011" division="truck" formnum="CTS-5078" date="05/08/1996">
        <title>STEERING COLUMN ASSEMBLY, STANDARD - 5000, 9000 CONV.</title>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>5000</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9200</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9300</truckmodel>
                <truckmodel>9400</truckmodel>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>The steering column assembly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501101">Figure 1</hotlnk>) provides the vehicle operator with control of the
                    steering from inside the vehicle cab. This manual covers the double-jointed column used in the 5000,
                    9200, 9300 and 9400 Series vehicles.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501101" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="g0501101" filename="../figg05/G0501101.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. Steering Assembly, Exploded View</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. STEERING WHEEL ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. HORN BUTTON</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. HORN BASE PLATE ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. STEERING WHEEL MOUNTING NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. SCREW</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. STEERING WHEEL</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. HORN BUTTON CONTACT RING</callout1>
                        <callout1>8. CONTACT ROLLER WITH CABLE</callout1>
                        <callout1>9. STEERING COLUMN FLANGE WITH BEARING</callout1>
                        <callout1>10. LOCK NUT</callout1>
                        <callout1>11. FLAT WASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>12. CLAMP BOLT</callout1>
                        <callout1>13. BEARING SPACER</callout1>
                        <callout1>14. BEARING SEAT</callout1>
                        <callout1>15. JACKET TUBE UPPER BEARING ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>16. STEERING SHAFT AND YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>17. JACKET TUBE</callout1>
                        <callout1>18. STEERING COLUMN BRACKET CAP</callout1>
                        <callout1>19. JACKET TUBE LOWER BEARING ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>20. BEARING SEAT</callout1>
                        <callout1>21. JACKET TUBE BEARING SPRING</callout1>
                        <callout1>22. DUST CAP</callout1>
                        <callout1>23. UNIVERSAL JOINT COVER</callout1>
                        <callout1>24. STEERING COLUMN MOUNTING BRACKET</callout1>
                        <callout1>25. STEERING COLUMN BRACE</callout1>
                        <callout1>26. UNIVERSAL JOINT</callout1>
                        <callout1>27. GREASE FITTING</callout1>
                        <callout1>28. SLIP YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>29. SLIP YOKE SEAL</callout1>
                        <callout1>30. STEERING SLIP SHAFT</callout1>
                        <callout1>31. SLIP YOKE SEAL WASHER</callout1>
                        <callout1>32. DUST CAP</callout1>
                        <callout1>33. LOWER END YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>34. UNIVERSAL JOINT</callout1>
                        <callout1>35. STEERING GEAR END YOKE</callout1>
                        <callout1>36. END YOKE PINCH BOLT, LOCK NUT, 7/16NF (REFER TO TORQUE CHART)</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>A steering wheel is connected to the upper steering shaft, which is held by two sets of ball
                    bearings in the steering column jacket tube. The steering shaft is connected to the slip shaft by a
                    universal joint. The lower end of the slip shaft is connected to the steering gear by a second
                    universal joint. The universal joints and slip shaft permit correct alignment and smooth rotation of
                    the steering shaft to steering gear with no binding of the shafts.
                </para>
                <para>The turn signal and trailer brake controls are mounted to the steering column jacket tube.</para>
                <para>The horn will operate at any time and is not dependent on the ignition switch. To energize the
                    relay and feed current to the horn, a path to ground must be available. The path to ground is
                    completed through the horn button mechanism in the steering column.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
